{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1775862358821,"sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","part":{"id":"prt_d79a5230d001XzUyKTlt8oXKya","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","messageID":"msg_d79a505fb0012xNd0BlvuURJ7m","sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":17593,"input":4,"output":245,"reasoning":0,"cache":{"write":3204,"read":14140}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1775862367200,"sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","part":{"id":"prt_d79a543dd001RDD9CdxDXsyzW4","messageID":"msg_d79a5233b001FI1uGvYCeRZmCJ","sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","snapshot":"f33c5114db06c230ebdbad281b75532a26b6f114","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775862373732,"sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","part":{"id":"prt_d79a54948001s7Xj7UoLaIZikU","messageID":"msg_d79a5233b001FI1uGvYCeRZmCJ","sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:3","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/proposal.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/proposal.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-011 — Router JWT 认证与签发 (Router JWT Authentication and Issuance)\n2: \n3: ## Purpose\n4: \n5: Implement JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication and issuance functionality in `pkg/router` to provide secure, stateless authentication for requests between the Router and sandbox pods. The JWT Manager serves as the security foundation for the AgentCube routing layer, handling RSA key generation, token signing, and key persistence in Kubernetes secrets.\n6: \n7: The JWT Manager provides three primary responsibilities:\n8: 1. **Token Generation**: Creates RS256-signed JWT tokens with configurable claims for session identification\n9: 2. **Key Management**: Generates and persists RSA 2048-bit key pairs, with automatic storage in Kubernetes secrets for cluster resilience\n10: 3. **Authentication**: Signs proxied requests to sandbox pods, enabling the sandbox to verify request authenticity\n11: \n12: This AR builds upon the HTTP reverse proxy core (AR-009) and session management (AR-010) to add the security layer required for trusted communication between Router and sandboxes.\n13: \n14: ---\n15: \n16: ## Scope\n17: \n18: ### In scope\n19: \n20: | Item | Detail |\n21: |------|--------|\n22: | **Package** | `github.com/volcano-sh/agentcube/pkg/router` |\n23: | **Core functionality** | JWT token generation (RS256), RSA key pair management, Kubernetes secret persistence |\n24: | **Integration with** | Kubernetes API (Secret storage), Router HTTP handlers (token injection) |\n25: | **Token claims** | Standard claims (exp, iat, iss) + custom claims (session_id) |\n26: | **Key storage** | Kubernetes Secret `picod-router-identity` with `private.pem` and `public.pem` |\n27: | **Configuration** | Namespace via `AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` env var (default: `default`) |\n28: | **Algorithm** | RS256 (RSA with SHA-256) |\n29: \n30: ### Out of scope\n31: \n32: - JWT token validation/verification (handled by sandbox pods consuming the tokens)\n33: - OAuth2/OIDC integration (bearer token authentication is AR-012)\n34: - Certificate-based authentication (mTLS handled separately)\n35: - Token refresh mechanism (short-lived 5-minute tokens, sessions manage lifecycle)\n36: - JWT revocation list (rely on short expiration and session termination)\n37: - Key rotation automation (initial implementation uses fixed keys per deployment)\n38: \n39: ---\n40: \n41: ## Design\n42: \n43: ### File layout\n44: \n45: | File | Role |\n46: |------|------|\n47: | `pkg/router/jwt.go` | **EXISTING/ENHANCED** — JWTManager implementation, key generation, token signing |\n48: \n49: ### Type definitions\n50: \n51: **`JWTManager`** — JWT management struct:\n52: \n53: ```go\n54: // JWTManager handles JWT key generation and token signing.\n55: type JWTManager struct {\n56:     privateKey *rsa.PrivateKey\n57:     publicKey  *rsa.PublicKey\n58:     clientset  kubernetes.Interface\n59: }\n60: ```\n61: \n62: **Key methods:**\n63: \n64: ```go\n65: // NewJWTManager creates a new JWTManager with a generated RSA key pair.\n66: func NewJWTManager() (*JWTManager, error)\n67: \n68: // GenerateToken creates a JWT with the given claims.\n69: func (m *JWTManager) GenerateToken(claims map[string]interface{}) (string, error)\n70: \n71: // GetPublicKeyPEM returns the public key in PEM format.\n72: func (m *JWTManager) GetPublicKeyPEM() ([]byte, error)\n73: \n74: // GetPrivateKeyPEM returns the private key in PEM format.\n75: func (m *JWTManager) GetPrivateKeyPEM() ([]byte, error)\n76: \n77: // TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret attempts to store keys in K8s secret or load existing.\n78: func (m *JWTManager) TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret() error\n79: ```\n80: \n81: ### Token Generation Flow\n82: \n83: ```\n84: HTTP Request Received\n85:          │\n86:          ▼\n87: Session Resolved (AR-010)\n88:          │\n89:          ▼\n90: JWTManager.GenerateToken\n91:          │\n92:     ┌────┴────┐\n93:     ▼         ▼\n94: Base Claims   Custom Claims\n95: - exp         - session_id\n96: - iat         (from SessionInfo)\n97: - iss         \n98:     │         │\n99:     └────┬────┘\n100:          ▼\n101: Sign with RS256\n102: (private key)\n103:          │\n104:          ▼\n105: Authorization: Bearer <token>\n106: (set on proxied request)\n107: ```\n108: \n109: ### Key Persistence Flow\n110: \n111: ```\n112: Server Startup\n113:          │\n114:          ▼\n115: NewJWTManager()\n116: (generate new RSA key pair)\n117:          │\n118:          ▼\n119: TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret\n120:          │\n121:     ┌────┴─────────────────┐\n122:     │                      │\n123: In-cluster?            Not in-cluster\n124:     │                      │\n125:     ▼                      ▼\n126: Create Secret          Log warning\n127: (or load existing)     Use ephemeral keys\n128:          │\n129:          ▼\n130: Secret 'picod-router-identity'\n131: ├── private.pem (RSA PRIVATE KEY)\n132: └── public.pem  (PUBLIC KEY)\n133: ```\n134: \n135: ### Token Claims Structure\n136: \n137: ```go\n138: // Base claims (always included)\n139: {\n140:     \"exp\": <unix_timestamp>,      // Expiration: now + 5 minutes\n141:     \"iat\": <unix_timestamp>,      // Issued at: now\n142:     \"iss\": \"agentcube-router\"     // Issuer\n143: }\n144: \n145: // With custom claims\n146: {\n147:     \"exp\": 1710000000,\n148:     \"iat\": 1709999700,\n149:     \"iss\": \"agentcube-router\",\n150:     \"session_id\": \"sess-abc-123\"  // From SessionInfo.SessionID\n151: }\n152: ```\n153: \n154: ### Constants\n155: \n156: | Name | Value | Description |\n157: |------|-------|-------------|\n158: | `rsaKeySize` | `2048` | RSA key size in bits |\n159: | `jwtExpiration` | `5 * time.Minute` | Token validity duration |\n160: | `identitySecretName` | `\"picod-router-identity\"` | Kubernetes Secret name |\n161: | `privateKeyDataKey` | `\"private.pem\"` | Secret data key for private key |\n162: | `publicKeyDataKey` | `\"public.pem\"` | Secret data key for public key |\n163: \n164: ### Environment Variables\n165: \n166: | Variable | Default | Description |\n167: |----------|---------|-------------|\n168: | `AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` | `\"default\"` | Namespace for JWT identity secret |\n169: \n170: ---\n171: \n172: ## Impact Analysis\n173: \n174: ### Files created/modified\n175: \n176: | File | Lines (est.) | Type |\n177: |------|-------------|------|\n178: | `pkg/router/jwt.go` | ~220 | Enhanced/Complete |\n179: \n180: ### Downstream consumers\n181: \n182: | Consumer | Dependency |\n183: |----------|-----------|\n184: | Router (AR-009) | Uses JWTManager to sign proxied requests |\n185: | Session Manager (AR-010) | Provides session_id for token claims |\n186: | Sandbox Pods | Validate JWT tokens using public key |\n187: | Kubernetes API | Secret storage for key persistence |\n188: \n189: ### Breaking change risk\n190: \n191: - **None for existing APIs**: JWT is additive security enhancement\n192: - **Key format**: Standard PKCS1/PKIX PEM format, widely compatible\n193: - **Secret naming**: Uses `picod-router-identity` which doesn't conflict with existing secrets\n194: - **Algorithm**: RS256 is standard JWT algorithm, well-supported\n195: \n196: ---\n197: \n198: ## Alternatives Considered\n199: \n200: ### 1. Use HMAC (HS256) instead of RSA (RS256)\n201: \n202: **Approach**: Use shared secret key for both signing and verification.\n203: \n204: **Rejected because**: RSA allows public key distribution to sandboxes without exposing the private signing key. With HMAC, any sandbox that can verify tokens would need the secret key, creating a security risk if compromised.\n205: \n206: ### 2. Use Kubernetes Service Account tokens instead of custom JWT\n207: \n208: **Approach**: Use `TokenRequest` API to generate projected service account tokens for each request.\n209: \n210: **Rejected because**: Service account tokens have different semantics (identity of the Router pod vs. identity of the session). They also have different expiration patterns and aren't suitable for session-scoped claims.\n211: \n212: ### 3. Use external key management service (KMS/Vault)\n213: \n214: **Approach**: Integrate with HashiCorp Vault or cloud KMS for key storage.\n215: \n216: **Rejected because**: Adds external dependency and complexity. For the initial implementation, Kubernetes Secret storage provides sufficient security with lower operational overhead. Can be migrated to external KMS later if required.\n217: \n218: ### 4. Generate new keys on each pod restart\n219: \n220: **Approach**: Always generate ephemeral keys, don't persist to secrets.\n221: \n222: **Rejected because**: Would invalidate all active sessions on Router restart. Key persistence ensures session continuity across Router restarts and rolling updates.\n223: \n224: ### 5. Use Ed25519 instead of RSA\n225: \n226: **Approach**: Use Ed25519 signatures for smaller key sizes and faster operations.\n227: \n228: **Rejected because**: While Ed25519 is preferred for new designs, RSA-2048 is more widely supported by JWT libraries in various languages. RSA was chosen for maximum compatibility with sandbox implementations.\n229: \n230: ---\n231: \n232: ## Dependencies\n233: \n234: | Dependency | Version | Purpose |\n235: |------------|---------|---------|\n236: | `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` | v5.x | JWT token signing |\n237: | `k8s.io/client-go` | v0.34.1 | Kubernetes Secret CRUD |\n238: | `k8s.io/api` | v0.34.1 | Secret API types |\n239: | `k8s.io/apimachinery` | v0.34.1 | API machinery |\n240: | `k8s.io/klog/v2` | v2.x | Structured logging |\n241: \n242: ---\n243: \n244: ## Verification\n245: \n246: ```bash\n247: # Unit tests\n248: make test PKG=./pkg/router/...\n249: \n250: # Integration tests\n251: go test -v ./pkg/router/... -run \"TestJWTManager\"\n252: go test -v ./pkg/router/... -run \"TestGenerateToken\"\n253: go test -v ./pkg/router/... -run \"TestKeyPersistence\"\n254: \n255: # Build verification\n256: go build ./pkg/router/...\n257: \n258: # Verify JWT token format\n259: go test -v ./pkg/router/... -run \"TestTokenClaims\"\n260: \n261: # Verify race conditions\n262: go test -race ./pkg/router/...\n263: ```\n264: \n265: ---\n266: \n267: ## References\n268: \n269: - [Session Routing Design](session-routing/design.md) — Router design details\n270: - [Session Routing Specification](session-routing/spec.md) — Functional requirements\n271: - [AR-009](changes/AR-009/design.md) — Router HTTP Reverse Proxy Core\n272: - [AR-010](changes/AR-010/design.md) — Router Session Management\n273: - [JWT Specification](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7519) — RFC 7519\n274: - [JWS Specification](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7515) — RFC 7515 (RS256)\n275: \n276: ---\n277: \n278: *AR-011 — Module: pkg/router — Language: Go — Size: M*\n\n(End of file - total 278 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-011 — Router JWT 认证与签发 (Router JWT Authentication and Issuance)\n\n## Purpose\n\nImplement JWT (JSON Web Token) authentication and issuance functionality in `pkg/router` to provide secure, stateless authentication for requests between the Router and sandbox pods. The JWT Manager serves as the security foundation for the AgentCube routing layer, handling RSA key generation, token signing, and key persistence in Kubernetes secrets.\n\nThe JWT Manager provides three primary responsibilities:\n1. **Token Generation**: Creates RS256-signed JWT tokens with configurable claims for session identification\n2. **Key Management**: Generates and persists RSA 2048-bit key pairs, with automatic storage in Kubernetes secrets for cluster resilience\n3. **Authentication**: Signs proxied requests to sandbox pods, enabling the sandbox to verify request authenticity\n\nThis AR builds upon the HTTP reverse proxy core (AR-009) and session management (AR-010) to add the security layer required for trusted communication between Router and sandboxes.\n\n---\n\n## Scope\n\n### In scope\n\n| Item | Detail |","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/proposal.md","time":{"start":1775862373713,"end":1775862373730}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775862373735,"sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","part":{"id":"prt_d79a55be70019K0PEqju1FjZFF","messageID":"msg_d79a5233b001FI1uGvYCeRZmCJ","sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","type":"tool","tool":"glob","callID":"toolu_functions.glob:6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"**/router/**"},"output":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/pkg/router/session_manager.go\n/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/pkg/router/jwt.go\n/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/pkg/router/errors.go\n/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/pkg/router/config.go\n/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/pkg/router/doc.go","metadata":{"count":5,"truncated":false},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z","time":{"start":1775862373720,"end":1775862373734}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775862373739,"sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","part":{"id":"prt_d79a54f020017uDAWWaomnBoLH","messageID":"msg_d79a5233b001FI1uGvYCeRZmCJ","sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:4","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-011/delta-spec.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-011/delta-spec.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-011: Router JWT 认证与签发 - Delta Specification\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: **AR ID:** AR-011  \n6: **Module:** `pkg/router`  \n7: **Language:** Go  \n8: **Size:** M  \n9: **Base Spec:** [deployment/client-go.md](../../deployment/client-go.md), [pkg/router/jwt.go](../../pkg/router/jwt.go)\n10: \n11: The Router JWT Authentication and Issuance component provides RSA-based JWT token generation, signing, and key management for the AgentCube router. It enables secure authentication between the router and the Workload Manager by generating signed JWT tokens with session-specific claims, while persisting RSA key pairs in Kubernetes Secrets for cluster-wide accessibility.\n12: \n13: ---\n14: \n15: ## Requirements\n16: \n17: ### Requirement: RSA Key Pair Generation\n18: \n19: The system SHALL generate cryptographically secure RSA key pairs for JWT signing.\n20: \n21: #### Scenario: Generate new RSA key pair on initialization\n22: - **GIVEN** a fresh router instance starting without existing keys\n23: - **WHEN** `NewJWTManager()` is called\n24: - **THEN** the system SHALL generate a 2048-bit RSA key pair\n25: - **AND** return a `JWTManager` with the private and public keys initialized\n26: \n27: #### Scenario: RSA key generation uses secure random source\n28: - **GIVEN** the router requires a new JWT signing key\n29: - **WHEN** the RSA key is generated using `rsa.GenerateKey(rand.Reader, 2048)`\n30: - **THEN** the key SHALL be generated using cryptographically secure random source\n31: - **AND** the private key SHALL be suitable for RS256 signing\n32: \n33: #### Scenario: Handle RSA generation failure\n34: - **GIVEN** the system is unable to generate RSA keys due to resource constraints\n35: - **WHEN** `NewJWTManager()` is called and key generation fails\n36: - **THEN** the system SHALL return an error with message \"failed to generate RSA key\"\n37: \n38: ---\n39: \n40: ### Requirement: JWT Token Generation and Signing\n41: \n42: The system SHALL generate and sign JWT tokens with configurable claims using RS256 algorithm.\n43: \n44: #### Scenario: Generate token with custom claims\n45: - **GIVEN** a `JWTManager` initialized with valid RSA keys\n46: - **AND** a claims map containing `{\\\"session_id\\\": \\\"sess-abc-123\\\", \\\"user\\\": \\\"test-user\\\"}`\n47: - **WHEN** `GenerateToken(claims)` is called\n48: - **THEN** the system SHALL return a signed JWT string containing all custom claims\n49: \n50: #### Scenario: JWT includes standard claims automatically\n51: - **GIVEN** a `JWTManager` with valid RSA keys\n52: - **WHEN** any token is generated via `GenerateToken()`\n53: - **THEN** the token SHALL include the following standard claims:\n54:   - `exp`: expiration time (current time + 5 minutes)\n55:   - `iat`: issued at time (current timestamp)\n56:   - `iss`: issuer (\"agentcube-router\")\n57: \n58: #### Scenario: JWT uses RS256 signing algorithm\n59: - **GIVEN** a `JWTManager` with RSA private key\n60: - **WHEN** `GenerateToken()` is called with any claims\n61: - **THEN** the token SHALL be signed using `jwt.SigningMethodRS256`\n62: - **AND** the signature SHALL be verifiable with the corresponding public key\n63: \n64: #### Scenario: Handle signing failure\n65: - **GIVEN** a `JWTManager` with corrupted or invalid private key\n66: - **WHEN** `GenerateToken()` is called\n67: - **THEN** the system SHALL return an error with message \"failed to sign token\"\n68: \n69: #### Scenario: Token expiration is configurable via claims override\n70: - **GIVEN** a `JWTManager` with valid keys\n71: - **AND** a claims map containing a custom `exp` value\n72: - **WHEN** `GenerateToken(claims)` is called\n73: - **THEN** the custom expiration SHALL override the default 5-minute expiration\n74: \n75: ---\n76: \n77: ### Requirement: RSA Key PEM Encoding\n78: \n79: The system SHALL provide methods to export RSA keys in standard PEM format.\n80: \n81: #### Scenario: Export public key in PEM format\n82: - **GIVEN** a `JWTManager` initialized with an RSA key pair\n83: - **WHEN** `GetPublicKeyPEM()` is called\n84: - **THEN** the system SHALL return the public key encoded as PKIX PEM format\n85: - **AND** the PEM block type SHALL be \"PUBLIC KEY\"\n86: \n87: #### Scenario: Export private key in PEM format\n88: - **GIVEN** a `JWTManager` initialized with an RSA key pair\n89: - **WHEN** `GetPrivateKeyPEM()` is called\n90: - **THEN** the system SHALL return the private key encoded as PKCS#1 PEM format\n91: - **AND** the PEM block type SHALL be \"RSA PRIVATE KEY\"\n92: \n93: #### Scenario: PEM encoding for key storage\n94: - **GIVEN** keys need to be stored in Kubernetes Secrets\n95: - **WHEN** `GetPublicKeyPEM()` and `GetPrivateKeyPEM()` are called\n96: - **THEN** the returned byte slices SHALL be valid UTF-8 strings\n97: - **AND** they SHALL be parseable by standard PEM decoders\n98: \n99: ---\n100: \n101: ### Requirement: Kubernetes Secret Key Storage\n102: \n103: The system SHALL persist and retrieve RSA keys from Kubernetes Secrets for cluster-wide access.\n104: \n105: #### Scenario: Create new secret when none exists\n106: - **GIVEN** the router is running in a Kubernetes cluster\n107: - **AND** no secret named `picod-router-identity` exists in the configured namespace\n108: - **WHEN** `TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret()` is called\n109: - **THEN** the system SHALL create a new Secret with:\n110:   - Name: `picod-router-identity`\n111:   - Namespace: `$AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` (or \"default\")\n112:   - Labels: `app=agentcube`, `component=router`\n113:   - Data keys: `private.pem`, `public.pem`\n114: \n115: #### Scenario: Load existing keys from secret\n116: - **GIVEN** a secret `picod-router-identity` already exists in the namespace\n117: - **AND** the secret contains valid `private.pem` and `public.pem` data\n118: - **WHEN** `TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret()` is called\n119: - **THEN** the system SHALL load the existing keys into the `JWTManager`\n120: - **AND** the loaded keys SHALL replace the ephemeral keys\n121: \n122: #### Scenario: Handle non-cluster environment gracefully\n123: - **GIVEN** the router is NOT running in a Kubernetes cluster\n124: - **WHEN** `TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret()` is called\n125: - **THEN** the system SHALL log a warning message\n126: - **AND** return nil (no error) to continue with ephemeral keys\n127: \n128: #### Scenario: Handle Kubernetes client creation failure\n129: - **GIVEN** the router is running in-cluster but cannot create Kubernetes client\n130: - **WHEN** `TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret()` attempts to create the clientset\n131: - **THEN** the system SHALL return an error with message \"failed to create Kubernetes client\"\n132: \n133: #### Scenario: Handle secret creation failure\n134: - **GIVEN** the router has valid Kubernetes client\n135: - **AND** secret creation fails for reasons other than AlreadyExists\n136: - **WHEN** attempting to create the JWT secret\n137: - **THEN** the system SHALL return an error with message \"failed to create JWT secret\"\n138: \n139: #### Scenario: Handle malformed key data in existing secret\n140: - **GIVEN** an existing secret with invalid or corrupted `private.pem` data\n141: - **WHEN** `loadExistingSecret()` attempts to parse the key\n142: - **THEN** the system SHALL return an error indicating key parsing failure\n143: \n144: ---\n145: \n146: ### Requirement: JWT Key Loading from PEM\n147: \n148: The system SHALL be able to parse and load RSA private keys from PEM-encoded data.\n149: \n150: #### Scenario: Load private key from valid PEM data\n151: - **GIVEN** valid PKCS#1 RSA private key PEM data\n152: - **WHEN** `loadPrivateKeyPEM()` is called with the PEM bytes\n153: - **THEN** the system SHALL parse and set the private key\n154: - **AND** derive and set the corresponding public key\n155: \n156: #### Scenario: Handle invalid PEM block\n157: - **GIVEN** PEM data that cannot be decoded\n158: - **WHEN** `loadPrivateKeyPEM()` is called\n159: - **THEN** the system SHALL return an error with message \"failed to decode PEM block\"\n160: \n161: #### Scenario: Handle invalid PKCS#1 key data\n162: - **GIVEN** PEM data with valid structure but invalid key content\n163: - **WHEN** `loadPrivateKeyPEM()` attempts to parse the key\n164: - **THEN** the system SHALL return an error with message \"failed to parse private key\"\n165: \n166: ---\n167: \n168: ### Requirement: Namespace Configuration\n169: \n170: The system SHALL support configurable namespace for JWT secret storage.\n171: \n172: #### Scenario: Default namespace is \"default\"\n173: - **GIVEN** the `AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` environment variable is not set\n174: - **WHEN** the router package is initialized\n175: - **THEN** `IdentityNamespace` SHALL default to \"default\"\n176: \n177: #### Scenario: Namespace from environment variable\n178: - **GIVEN** the `AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` environment variable is set to \"agentcube-system\"\n179: - **WHEN** the router package is initialized\n180: - **THEN** `IdentityNamespace` SHALL be set to \"agentcube-system\"\n181: \n182: ---\n183: \n184: ### Requirement: Token Validation Support\n185: \n186: The system SHALL provide capabilities to validate JWT tokens using the stored public key.\n187: \n188: #### Scenario: Validate token signature\n189: - **GIVEN** a JWT token signed by the `JWTManager`'s private key\n190: - **AND** the corresponding public key is available\n191: - **WHEN** the token is validated using the public key\n192: - **THEN** the signature SHALL be verified successfully\n193: \n194: #### Scenario: Reject token with invalid signature\n195: - **GIVEN** a JWT token signed with a different key\n196: - **WHEN** validation is attempted with the current public key\n197: - **THEN** the validation SHALL fail with a signature error\n198: \n199: #### Scenario: Reject expired token\n200: - **GIVEN** a JWT token that has exceeded its `exp` claim time\n201: - **WHEN** the token is validated\n202: - **THEN** the validation SHALL fail with an expiration error\n203: \n204: ---\n205: \n206: ## Changes to Base Specification\n207: \n208: No modifications to existing interfaces. This AR adds new JWT management capabilities.\n209: \n210: ---\n211: \n212: ## New Interfaces\n213: \n214: ### JWTManager\n215: \n216: ```go\n217: // JWTManager handles RSA key generation, JWT token signing, and key persistence.\n218: type JWTManager struct {\n219:     privateKey *rsa.PrivateKey    // RSA private key for signing\n220:     publicKey  *rsa.PublicKey     // RSA public key for verification\n221:     clientset  kubernetes.Interface // Kubernetes client for secret operations\n222: }\n223: ```\n224: \n225: #### Methods\n226: \n227: | Method | Signature | Description |\n228: |--------|-----------|-------------|\n229: | `NewJWTManager` | `func NewJWTManager() (*JWTManager, error)` | Creates new JWTManager with generated RSA key pair |\n230: | `GenerateToken` | `func (m *JWTManager) GenerateToken(claims map[string]interface{}) (string, error)` | Creates and signs JWT with custom claims |\n231: | `GetPublicKeyPEM` | `func (m *JWTManager) GetPublicKeyPEM() ([]byte, error)` | Returns public key in PKIX PEM format |\n232: | `GetPrivateKeyPEM` | `func (m *JWTManager) GetPrivateKeyPEM() ([]byte, error)` | Returns private key in PKCS#1 PEM format |\n233: | `TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret` | `func (m *JWTManager) TryStoreOrLoadJWTKeySecret() error` | Stores or loads keys from Kubernetes Secret |\n234: \n235: ---\n236: \n237: ## Modified Interfaces\n238: \n239: None. This AR introduces new functionality without modifying existing interfaces.\n240: \n241: ---\n242: \n243: ## Behavioral Changes\n244: \n245: | Behavior | Before | After |\n246: |----------|--------|-------|\n247: | JWT signing | Not supported | RS256-signed JWT with configurable claims |\n248: | Key persistence | Ephemeral only | Kubernetes Secret storage with fallback |\n249: | Key generation | None | 2048-bit RSA key generation on startup |\n250: | Token standard claims | None | exp, iat, iss auto-populated |\n251: | Cross-pod key sharing | Not possible | Via Kubernetes Secret in configured namespace |\n252: \n253: ---\n254: \n255: ## Dependencies\n256: \n257: | Dependency | Version | Purpose |\n258: |------------|---------|---------|\n259: | `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` | v5.x | JWT token creation and signing |\n260: | `k8s.io/client-go` | v0.34.1 | Kubernetes client for Secret operations |\n261: | `k8s.io/api/core/v1` | v0.34.1 | Secret type definitions |\n262: | `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/apis/meta/v1` | v0.34.1 | Kubernetes metadata types |\n263: | `k8s.io/apimachinery/pkg/api/errors` | v0.34.1 | Kubernetes API error handling |\n264: | `k8s.io/klog/v2` | Latest | Structured logging |\n265: | `crypto/rsa` | Standard library | RSA key generation |\n266: | `crypto/x509` | Standard library | Key encoding/decoding |\n267: | `encoding/pem` | Standard library | PEM format handling |\n268: | `crypto/rand` | Standard library | Secure random number generation |\n269: \n270: ---\n271: \n272: ## File Index\n273: \n274: | Path | Purpose |\n275: |------|---------|\n276: | `pkg/router/jwt.go` | JWTManager implementation with key generation, token signing, and secret storage |\n277: | `pkg/router/errors.go` | JWT-specific error types (`JWTSigningError`) |\n278: | `pkg/router/config.go` | Configuration constants (e.g., `IdentityNamespace` initialization) |\n279: \n280: ---\n281: \n282: ## Constants\n283: \n284: | Constant | Value | Description |\n285: |----------|-------|-------------|\n286: | `rsaKeySize` | `2048` | RSA key bit length |\n287: | `jwtExpiration` | `5 * time.Minute` | Default token expiration duration |\n288: | `identitySecretName` | `\"picod-router-identity\"` | Kubernetes Secret name for key storage |\n289: | `privateKeyDataKey` | `\"private.pem\"` | Secret data key for private key |\n290: | `publicKeyDataKey` | `\"public.pem\"` | Secret data key for public key |\n291: | `IdentityNamespace` | `\"default\"` or `$AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` | Namespace for JWT secret storage |\n292: \n293: ---\n294: \n295: ## API Endpoints Summary\n296: \n297: This AR provides library functionality; no HTTP endpoints are directly exposed.\n298: \n299: | Consumer | Usage |\n300: |----------|-------|\n301: | SessionManager | JWT tokens for Workload Manager authentication |\n302: | Router Server | Token generation for session claims |\n303: \n304: ---\n305: \n306: ## Migration Notes\n307: \n308: - **New dependency**: Add `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` to go.mod\n309: - **RBAC requirement**: Router requires permission to create/get Secrets in the target namespace\n310: - **Secret naming**: Uses `picod-router-identity` Secret name; ensure no conflicts\n311: - **Namespace configuration**: Set `AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` env var for non-default namespace\n312: - **Key rotation**: To rotate keys, delete the `picod-router-identity` Secret; new keys will be generated\n313: \n314: ---\n315: \n316: ## Acceptance Criteria Summary\n317: \n318: 1. **Key Generation**: RSA-2048 keys are generated on `NewJWTManager()` with secure random source\n319: 2. **Token Creation**: `GenerateToken()` produces valid RS256-signed JWTs with standard and custom claims\n320: 3. **Key Persistence**: Keys are stored in and loaded from Kubernetes Secret `picod-router-identity`\n321: 4. **PEM Encoding**: Keys can be exported in standard PEM format for external use\n322: 5. **Error Handling**: All failure scenarios return descriptive errors without panicking\n323: 6. **Namespace Support**: Secret namespace is configurable via `AGENTCUBE_NAMESPACE` environment variable\n324: 7. **Non-cluster Fallback**: Gracefully handles non-Kubernetes environments with ephemeral keys\n325: 8. **Token Validation**: Generated tokens can be validated using the stored public key\n\n(End of file - total 325 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-011: Router JWT 认证与签发 - Delta Specification\n\n## Overview\n\n**AR ID:** AR-011  \n**Module:** `pkg/router`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** M  \n**Base Spec:** [deployment/client-go.md](../../deployment/client-go.md), [pkg/router/jwt.go](../../pkg/router/jwt.go)\n\nThe Router JWT Authentication and Issuance component provides RSA-based JWT token generation, signing, and key management for the AgentCube router. It enables secure authentication between the router and the Workload Manager by generating signed JWT tokens with session-specific claims, while persisting RSA key pairs in Kubernetes Secrets for cluster-wide accessibility.\n\n---\n\n## Requirements\n\n### Requirement: RSA Key Pair Generation\n\nThe system SHALL generate cryptographically secure RSA key pairs for JWT signing.\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-011/delta-spec.md","time":{"start":1775862373715,"end":1775862373737}}}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1775862373742,"sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","part":{"id":"prt_d79a55599001suDXEjoxTO5DD3","messageID":"msg_d79a5233b001FI1uGvYCeRZmCJ","sessionID":"ses_2865b0a75ffepxYCm60X9v5r8p","type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"toolu_functions.read:5","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-011/design.md"},"output":"<path>/home/dsj/benchmark/workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-011/design.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # AR-011 Design: Router JWT 认证与签发\n2: \n3: ## Overview\n4: \n5: **AR ID:** AR-011  \n6: **Module:** `pkg/router`  \n7: **Language:** Go  \n8: **Size:** Medium\n9: \n10: _TBD: Design overview for JWT authentication and issuance component_\n11: \n12: ---\n13: \n14: ## Architecture\n15: \n16: ### High-Level Design\n17: \n18: _TBD: Architecture diagram and component overview_\n19: \n20: ### Component Interactions\n21: \n22: | Component | Purpose | Input | Output |\n23: |-----------|---------|-------|--------|\n24: | **JWTManager** | _TBD_ | _TBD_ | _TBD_ |\n25: \n26: ---\n27: \n28: ## Directory Structure\n29: \n30: ```\n31: pkg/router/\n32: ├── doc.go                      # Package documentation\n33: ├── config.go                   # Router configuration\n34: ├── server.go                   # HTTP server\n35: ├── jwt.go                      # JWT management (_TBD: implement_)\n36: └── ...\n37: ```\n38: \n39: ---\n40: \n41: ## Data Structures\n42: \n43: ### Core Types\n44: \n45: _TBD: Define JWTManager interface and implementation_\n46: \n47: ---\n48: \n49: ## API Contracts\n50: \n51: _TBD: Define API methods and behaviors_\n52: \n53: ---\n54: \n55: ## Error Handling\n56: \n57: ### Error Types\n58: \n59: _TBD: Define error types and handling patterns_\n60: \n61: ---\n62: \n63: ## Testing Strategy\n64: \n65: _TBD: Unit and integration test approach_\n66: \n67: ---\n68: \n69: ## Dependencies\n70: \n71: ### Direct Dependencies\n72: \n73: | Dependency | Version | Purpose |\n74: |------------|---------|---------|\n75: | `github.com/golang-jwt/jwt/v5` | v5.x | JWT token handling |\n76: | `k8s.io/client-go` | v0.34.1 | Kubernetes Secret storage |\n77: \n78: ---\n79: \n80: ## Configuration\n81: \n82: ### Environment Variables\n83: \n84: | Variable | Default | Description |\n85: |----------|---------|-------------|\n86: | _TBD_ | _TBD_ | _TBD_ |\n87: \n88: ---\n89: \n90: ## Metrics\n91: \n92: _TBD: Prometheus metrics definition_\n93: \n94: ---\n95: \n96: ## Implementation Details\n97: \n98: _TBD: Key implementation details_\n99: \n100: ---\n101: \n102: ## References\n103: \n104: - [AR-009](changes/AR-009/design.md) — Router HTTP Reverse Proxy Core\n105: - [AR-010](changes/AR-010/design.md) — Router Session Management\n106: - [JWT Specification](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7519) — RFC 7519\n107: \n108: ---\n109: \n110: *AR-011 — Module: pkg/router — Language: Go — Size: M*\n\n(End of file - total 110 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# AR-011 Design: Router JWT 认证与签发\n\n## Overview\n\n**AR ID:** AR-011  \n**Module:** `pkg/router`  \n**Language:** Go  \n**Size:** Medium\n\n_TBD: Design overview for JWT authentication and issuance component_\n\n---\n\n## Architecture\n\n### High-Level Design\n\n_TBD: Architecture diagram and component overview_\n\n### Component Interactions","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"workspaces/v5.1/opencode-cli_bailian-coding-plan-kimi-k2.5_20260410T163138Z/changes/AR-011/design.md","time":{"start":1775862373717,"end":1775862373739}}}}
